# Constraint 0020

## Title
Advanced C++ coding standards (C++23/26)

## Description

This constraint applies to all code written in C++, except external dependencies (as coming in ext-projects). The following rules extend the basic CS-0010 constraints with state-of-the-art language, library and safety practices introduced in C++23, the upcoming C++26, and modern static-analysis tooling.

Regarding this constraint, the following rules apply:

- [CS-0020.47] Prefer `std::span` (or `gsl::span`) for non-owning array-like parameters instead of raw pointers or C-style arrays.
- [CS-0020.48] Prefer `std::expected<T, E>` (or `outcome<T, E>`) for error-propagation instead of exceptions in pure-logic functions.
- [CS-0020.49] Use `std::move_only_function` (or `std::function_ref`) for callbacks that do not need copy semantics.
- [CS-0020.50] When a function is logically `noexcept`, mark it `noexcept` and verify with `static_assert(noexcept(fn(...)))` in tests.
- [CS-0020.51] Prefer `std::format` (or `fmt::format`) over `printf`/`std::ostringstream` for string formatting.
- [CS-0020.52] Prefer `std::ranges` algorithms over classic STL algorithms when possible.
- [CS-0020.53] If modules are available, place public interface headers into named modules and import them instead of include-guards.
- [CS-0020.54] Prefer `co_await`/coroutines for asynchronous I/O or background work instead of manual thread creation.
- [CS-0020.55] Annotate branch-heavy functions with `[[likely]]`/`[[unlikely]]` where the probability is well-known.
- [CS-0020.56] Declare functions that allocate resources (e.g., file handles, sockets) as `[[nodiscard]]` to enforce handling of the returned object.
- [CS-0020.57] Prefer `constexpr` for any function that can be evaluated at compile time, including constructors, accessors, and simple algorithms.
- [CS-0020.58] When a function returns a container, return it by value and rely on NRVO / move semantics; never return a raw pointer to internal storage.
- [CS-0020.59] Avoid implicit conversions that can lose information (e.g., `int` -> `float`, `size_t` -> `int`). Use `explicit` constructors or `static_cast` with comment.
- [CS-0020.60] All public interfaces shall be annotated with `[[nodiscard]]` when the return value represents a resource, an error code, or a validation result.
- [CS-0020.61] All functions that may fail must document the failure mode in Doxygen (`@throws`, `@error`).
- [CS-0020.62] When a raw pointer is required, wrap it immediately in a `gsl::not_null<T*>` or `std::not_null<T*>` to guarantee non-nullness.
- [CS-0020.63] Prefer `std::unique_ptr<T[]>` or `std::span<T>` over manual `new[]`/`delete[]`. Use `std::vector<T>` only when size mutability is needed.
- [CS-0020.64] All `enum class` values used for bit-flags shall provide overloads for bitwise operators (`|`, `&`, `^`, `~`).
- [CS-0020.65] Never expose raw `char*` buffers; instead use `std::string_view` for read-only view and `std::span<std::byte>` for mutable raw data.
- [CS-0020.66] Enable AddressSanitizer (ASan), UndefinedBehaviorSanitizer (UBSan), and ThreadSanitizer (TSan) in all CI builds.
- [CS-0020.67] All `constexpr` functions must be `noexcept` unless the exception is part of the intended interface.
- [CS-0020.68] When a class owns a mutex, expose lock-guarded access via a `std::unique_lock<std::mutex>` returned by a private helper, never expose the raw `std::mutex`.
- [CS-0020.69] Never use the `volatile` qualifier on objects for synchronization; instead use `std::atomic` or proper mutexes.
- [CS-0020.70] Run `clang-tidy` with the `modernize-*`, `cppcoreguidelines-*`, `bugprone-*`, and `performance-*` modules on every CI build.
- [CS-0020.71] Configure `clang-format` to use the LLVM style with the following overrides: `AllowShortIfStatementsOnASingleLine: false`, `DerivePointerAlignment: false`, `AlignTrailingComments: true`.
- [CS-0020.72] Enforce `cppcheck` with `--enable=style,performance,portability,warning,missingInclude` and treat any warning as a build error.
- [CS-0020.73] Add a `pre-commit` hook that runs `git diff --cached | clang-tidy -p . -checks='*' -` and fails on any output.
- [CS-0020.74] All new code shall include a `static_assert` that checks the size of public structs when binary compatibility is required.
- [CS-0020.75] Use `-Werror=shadow`, `-Werror=unused-parameter`, `-Werror=sign-conversion`, `-Werror=conversion` in the compiler command line.
- [CS-0020.76] When a function is a template that can be instantiated with `char*` or `wchar_t*`, add a `static_assert(std::is_same_v<T, std::byte> || std::is_same_v<T, std::uint8_t>, "use std::span<std::byte> instead of raw char*")`.
- [CS-0020.77] Every public API must have a Doxygen comment that includes `@brief`, `@param`, `@return`, and `@throws` (if applicable).
- [CS-0020.78] All new rules (CS-0020.xx) must be reviewed and approved by at least one senior architect before merging.
- [CS-0020.79] Every rule that introduces a new library feature must include a minimal usage example in the guideline document.
- [CS-0020.80] Maintain a changelog (`doc/architecture/CS-0020_changelog.md`) that records the addition, modification, or removal of any rule, with date and rationale.

## Rationale

These rules capture modern best-practice guidance from the C++ Core Guidelines, the latest language and library revisions (C++23, forthcoming C++26), and industry-standard static-analysis tooling. They reinforce safety, correctness, and maintainability while encouraging developers to adopt the most expressive and efficient language constructs available.

## Verification

*Note: These methods are not exhaustive. The developer (human or agent) SHALL ensure that applied verification is effective to ensure compliance and SHALL add verifications if required on a case-by-case basis.*

Each rule must be covered by at least two scriptable verification methods:

- **Method 1: Compiler Diagnostics & Build Flags**
  - Enforce strict standard compliance and warnings [CS-0020.53, CS-0020.56 - CS-0020.60, CS-0020.66, CS-0020.70, CS-0020.72 - CS-0020.76, CS-0020.78] using `-std=c++23`, `-Werror=unused-result`, `-Werror=conversion`, and `-Werror=shadow`.
  - Compiler-enforced `static_assert` and template constraints verify [CS-0020.48, CS-0020.49, CS-0020.74, CS-0020.76].
- **Method 2: Advanced Static Analysis (`clang-tidy` & `cppcheck`)**
  - Run `clang-tidy` with `modernize-*`, `cppcoreguidelines-*`, `performance-*`, and `bugprone-*` modules. This verifies [CS-0020.47 - CS-0020.52, CS-0020.55 - CS-0020.57, CS-0020.59 - CS-0020.60, CS-0020.62 - CS-0020.65, CS-0020.67, CS-0020.68, CS-0020.70, CS-0020.72, CS-0020.75].
  - `cppcheck` with style and portability enabled acts as a second layer for [CS-0020.47, CS-0020.59, CS-0020.62, CS-0020.63, CS-0020.68, CS-0020.72].
- **Method 3: AST/Regex Grep Scripts**
  - CI scripts MUST `grep` for forbidden patterns and enforced constructs. This verifies [CS-0020.51 - CS-0020.55, CS-0020.61, CS-0020.64, CS-0020.68, CS-0020.69, CS-0020.71, CS-0020.73, CS-0020.74, CS-0020.76, CS-0020.77, CS-0020.79, CS-0020.80].
  - Doxygen verification scripts parse comments for mandatory tags [CS-0020.61, CS-0020.77].
- **Method 4: Sanitizers & CI Tooling**
  - Dynamic execution using AddressSanitizer, UndefinedBehaviorSanitizer, and ThreadSanitizer during tests verifies [CS-0020.47, CS-0020.50, CS-0020.54, CS-0020.58, CS-0020.62, CS-0020.63, CS-0020.65 - CS-0020.69, CS-0020.71].
  - Format enforcement [CS-0020.71] and pre-commit automation [CS-0020.73] are verified via CI job status.
- **Method 5: Manual Audit Tracking & Documentation Tools**
  - Architectural review [CS-0020.78], failure mode documentation [CS-0020.61], API documentation [CS-0020.77], usage examples [CS-0020.79], and changelog maintenance [CS-0020.80] MUST be verified by CI scripts checking for associated artifacts in each PR.

